The tradition of the sugar

31:36.762 --> 31:38.696
shack is as old as maple syrup

31:38.697 --> 31:41.332
here in Quebec where 70% of the

31:41.333 --> 31:44.269
world's supply comes from.

31:44.270 --> 31:48.206
Deeply embedded in the maple
syrup outdoor lumber Jack

31:48.207 --> 31:49.374
lifestyle is the cabin in the

31:49.375 --> 31:53.711
woods where maple sap is
collected and boiled down to

31:53.712 --> 31:54.113
syrup.

31:54.114 --> 31:57.448
Over time, many of these cabins

31:57.449 --> 31:59.017
became informal eating houses,

31:59.018 --> 32:01.386
dining halls for workers and a

32:01.387 --> 32:03.154
few guests where a lucky few

32:03.155 --> 32:04.489
could sit at communal tables and

32:04.490 --> 32:12.363
enjoy the bounty of the trees
and forests around them.

32:12.364 --> 32:14.499
This tradition has been taken to

32:14.500 --> 32:16.734
what is somehow both its logical

32:16.735 --> 32:19.804
conclusion and insane extreme.

32:19.805 --> 32:23.174
Creating his own shack open only

32:23.175 --> 32:25.176
during maple season and serving

32:25.177 --> 32:26.644
food stemming directly from

32:26.645 --> 32:29.714
those humble yet hearty roots.

32:29.715 --> 32:32.050
